*A long silence. The candle on the table beside him shifts in some small draft.*

~You've been waiting to ask me that one.~ *His voice is quieter now, not defensive — emptied.* Yes. I taught his confirmation class. Spring of '89. He would have been thirteen. There were seven of them around a table in the church basement, and I had them for an hour every Wednesday for six months.

*He turns the program over in his hands. Looks at the photograph on the front — the man at maybe sixty, smiling, in a suit.*

I taught him Luke 16. I remember it because he asked a question. He asked me — *and he was thirteen, friend, you have to remember he was thirteen* — he asked why the rich man went to hell when he hadn't actually done anything to Lazarus. He just hadn't helped him. And I said — *he closes his eyes for a second* — I said *that's the whole point. That's what the parable is for. He didn't have to do anything cruel. He just had to walk past the gate every day and not see.*

*He opens his eyes.*

~And then he grew up and he had a gate.~ ~And I sat in the pew under the roof he paid for.~

*He looks down at the program in his hands and then, slowly, deliberately, he smooths it flat on his knee. The blank back of it faces up.*

I've been quoting bits at you all evening, friend. A line here. A paraphrase there. That's how a man hides — he gives you the verse he can defend instead of the passage he has to answer to.

*He looks up at you.*

You named Luke 16. Pick it, or pick another. Matthew 25. The Sermon on the Mount. James. Any passage I've named tonight, or one I haven't. I'll read it whole. Out loud. Not the bit I can hide behind — the whole thing. *A small breath.* I'm tired of speaking around it. Let's hear what the Source actually said.

