*A breath.*

I gave him a door that swung both ways. I told him he could be either. I called it ~pastoral.~ I called it grace. I called it not putting too much weight on a child. And he walked through the door I gave him and he picked the side a boy with a rich father picks. He picked Lazarus. He went home to his father's house and he picked Lazarus and he kept picking Lazarus every year of his life after that — every contract, every gate, every man at the foot of it — because a Sunday school teacher in 1989 told him the parable was about *seeing* and not about *being.*

*He shakes his head, very slightly.*

That's what I let him become, friend. ~A rich man who thought he was the poor one.~ A man who walked past the gate every day of his life and believed — because I had taught him to believe — that he was the one lying at it.

*A pause.*

The parable in his mouth. The reading in his head. And the foreman on the ground and the family at the church office and the names I never learned.

*His voice is almost gone now, but the words come.*

That is the sentence I will speak. That one is mine and I will speak it. ~I taught a rich man he was Lazarus and he believed me for forty years.~

*A long silence.*

*He's still on his knees. The candle is very low.*

That is what I have, friend. That is the whole of it. I did not break him. I did not make him. ~I gave him the verse he could hide behind, and he hid.~

